hronologically. the chronological' b'entries allow comparisons between actual astronautical events and' b'speculative ventures. they also allow comparisons between' b'simultaneous events taking place in different countries. they reveal' b'connections, influences, and evolutions hitherto unsuspected. every' b'entry is accompanied by at least one illustration. nearly every' b'spacecraft concept is illustrated with a schematic drawing. this' b'allows accurate comparisons to be made between designss, to visualize' b'differences, similarities, and influences.' b'' b'this text will be of interest to students of astronautical history,' b'and also to model builders who would be interested in the schematic' b'diagrams. science fiction fans as well as aviation history buffs and' b'historians of science will also find this book to be fascinating. the' b'unique collection of illustrations makes it a visually attractive and' b'very interesting history of the spaceship.' b'' b'special features' b'' b'includes scale drawings of several hundred spacecraft, both real and' b'fictional' b'' b'contains scores of illustrations: artwork, drawings, and photos' b'contemporary with the subject. this includes extremely rare' b'illustrations from scarce books and novels, exclusive photos and' b'drawings fromsoviet spacecraft; rare stills from both famous and' b'obscure science fiction films, and unpublished photographs from nasa' b'archives' b'' b'an index, bibliography, and appendices are included.' b'' b'contents' b'' b'part i the archaeology of the spaceship b.c. to a.d.)' b'part ii the invention of the spaceship b'part iii the experimenters b'part iv the world war b'part v the golden age of the spaceship b'part vi the dawn of the space age to the present)' b'' b'about ron miller' b'' b"[the brochure has a page of stuff here; i'll try to hit the high" b'spots.]' b'' b"former art director for albert einstein planetarium at smithsonian's" b'national air and space museum' b'' b'member of inte